    faqs: [
      { question: "What is the current inflation rate in India?", answer: "India's CPI (Consumer Price Index) inflation target is 4% (RBI's medium-term target). Actual inflation varies: food inflation often 6-8%, core inflation (excluding food & fuel) around 4-5%. Use 5-6% for long-term financial planning." },
      { question: "How does inflation affect savings?", answer: "If savings earn less than inflation, real value falls. Example: FD at 7% with 6% inflation = only 1% real return. Equity investments historically outpace inflation by 6-8% annually over long periods, making them essential for wealth preservation." },
      { question: "What is real vs nominal return?", answer: "Nominal return: stated return (e.g., FD 7%). Real return: return after inflation. Real return = Nominal − Inflation (approximately). FD 7% − 6% inflation = 1% real return. Equity 12% − 6% inflation = 6% real return." },
      { question: "How much should I save for retirement considering inflation?", answer: "Apply the inflation factor to your current expenses. If monthly expenses are ₹50K now and you retire in 25 years with 6% inflation, you'll need ₹2.15L/month. Build a corpus that generates this inflation-adjusted income. Rule of thumb: 25-30× annual retirement expenses." },
      { question: "Which investments beat inflation in India?", answer: "Consistent inflation beaters: Equity mutual funds (12-15% vs 6% inflation), Real estate (8-12%), Gold (8-10%), REITs (8-10%). Inflation losers: Savings account (3-4%), FD only partially beats inflation. Always invest a portion in equity to preserve wealth." },
    ],
